- Map when using very related values
- Map dont need to know the complete list of types and values at compile time
- If you dont know the keys or values use a Map

## Types

- Concrete Types: something that we can actually kind of create a value of directly and the access it and change it and create new copies of it.
  ex map, struct, int, string

- Interface Type: We cant actually create a value directly out of this type, we can only create values out of the concrete types

- An interface can have different interfaces

# Goroutines

A goroutine is a lightweight thread managed by the Go runtime. Fetch requests at the same time.

```markdown
go f(x, y, z)
starts a new goroutine running
```

```markdown
f(x, y, z)
The evaluation of f, x, y, and z happens in the current goroutine and the execution of f happens in the new goroutine.
```

Goroutines run in the same address space, so access to shared memory must be synchronized

By using the `go` keyword, we run one more time the function inside that same goroutine. Executes a `go write`.

## Scheduler

- One CPU is only running the core inside of one Goroutine at a time.
- We rely on the scheduler to defer which routine is being executed, it runs one by the time.
- Multiple CPU's can run multiple schedulers at the same time

> Concurency is not parallelism

### Concurrency vrs Parallalelism

#### Concurrency

- A program is concurrent if it can run multiple routines at the same time.
- A concurrent program has ability to run different things at the same time, but no really at the same time.
- One core, can only pick on go routine at the time.
- It can switch very quicly between routines but will be only one being executed at the time.
- We dont necessarily have to wait for one gorut to finish before going to the other one

The scheduler handles this.

![Routine 1](data:image/png;base64,)

### Parallalellism

- Requires multiple CPUs.
- Can have multiple threads executed at the same time.
